            <hr>
            <details>
                <summary>Abstract</summary>
                <article class="has-text-justified p-2"> The manufacturing sector of Nigeria performed abysmally poor
                    since the oil boom era of the
                    70s as a follow up to crude oil discovery in 1956.This is evident by considering the value exports
                    from the manufacturing industry measured as a percentage of GDP recorded from the World
                    Development Indicator (2018), attached to the appendix. The objective of the study was to
                    determine if empirical analysis supports existence of Dutch Disease and de-industrialisation in
                    Nigerian manufacturing sector. Since Resource Movement Effect has been suggested as one
                    of the transmission mechanisms of Dutch Disease in oil exporting countries, data on
                    manufactures exports were regressed on data on manufacturing employment, agricultural
                    employment and service employment in line with the Dutch Disease theory using Error
                    Correction Model. The results showed that the manufacturing sector of Nigeria has suffered
                    from both direct and indirect de-industrialisation over the period, as the result proved that
                    labour moved away from the sector of manufacturing to both the energy sector and the
                    services sector. It was therefore, concluded that Dutch Disease exists in the manufacturing
                    sector and the problem of de-industrialisation led to the crowding out of manufacturing output.
                    It was therefore, suggested that Government should encourage manufacturers to boost their
                    employment level and that banks should extend more loans at affordable rate of interest to
                    manufacturers, agricultural sector should also be developed to provide raw materials for
                    manufacturing industries and finally, that Government should provide regular power and water
                    supply and make Nigerian economy politically stable to attract foreign investors to establish
                    more manufacturing industries.</article>
