            <details>
                <summary>Abstract</summary>
                <article class="has-text-justified p-2">Capacity development is a process of ownership and change, in that it makes people, and even
                    organizations and societies, to own the capabilities required to achieve their own development
                    goals. The capabilities are usually acquired through training, education, and the like. Therefore,
                    knowledge is a key determinant of capacity development. In this line, this paper examined the
                    effects of increased cost of acquiring knowledge on the capacity development of the students
                    of public universities in Nigeria, using Adekunle Ajasin University (AAU) as a case study. The
                    paper studied the effects of tuition fees increment on the students of AAU, where tuition fees
                    were increased largely in 2018. The effects of tuition fees increment were examined on three
                    factors that affect the acquirement of knowledge of students during schooling: students’
                    financial receipts; student’s academic performance; and students’ moral behaviour. Primary
                    data collected through the distribution of copies of a questionnaire were employed for the
                    analysis of the study. Using frequency counts and percentages to analyze collected data and
                    chi-square tests to examine the validity of relevant hypotheses, the study found that tuition
                    fees increment has negative effects on students on the three factors considered. This means
                    that unaffordable cost of knowledge is an obstacle to the capacity development of university
                    students. The findings have relevant policy implications for the governments of low-income
                    countries such as Nigeria, which include: (i) the need for the governments to adopt cost-
                    effective education strategies, in order to minimize the cost of knowledge; and (ii) the need
                    for the governments to re-structure education to make it to be driven by capacity development,
                    in order to attract more foreign aids to support education, in that the aids of international
                    development organizations are driven largely by capacity development, particularly beginning
                    from the 1990s when capacity development was discovered as an effective mechanism of
                    making development to work in the economy.</article>
            </details>
